# Character Escaping Examples in Zolt

## Basic Escaping

Escape special characters to display them literally:

This is not a \[link\] but literal text.
These are not \{attributes\} but literal braces.
This is not \|inline styled\|\| text.

## Escaping Lists

Prevent list creation:

This is \- not a list item
And another \- dash that won't create a list
Number: \1. Not a numbered list

## Escaping Code

Display backticks and code markers:

Use the \`print()\` function to output text.
This is not \``` a code block.

## Escaping Emphasis

Show literal asterisks and symbols:

This is \*\*not bold\*\*
This is //not italic//
This is \_\_not underlined\_\_

## Escaping Headers

Prevent header creation:

\# This is a level 1 heading in text
\## This is a level 2 heading in text

## Escaping Blockquotes

Display quote markers literally:

\> This looks like a quote but isn't
\> Another line

## Escaping Links

Show link syntax literally:

The syntax is \[text\]\(url\)
Or references: \[text\]\[ref\]

## Escaping Media Prefixes

Display media prefixes:

Not an image: \!\[alt\]\(url.jpg\)
Not a video: \!\![alt]\(video.mp4\)
Not audio: \?\?[alt]\(audio.mp3\)

## Escaping Inline Styling

Show inline styling syntax:

This is not \|\|styled\|\|\{attr\} text.

## Escaping Variables

Display variable syntax literally:

The variable syntax is \{\$variable\}
Or calculations: \{\{ 10 + 5 \}\}

## Escaping Tables

Show table syntax:

\| Header 1 \| Header 2 \|
\| --- \| --- \|
\| Data 1 \| Data 2 \|

## Escaping Footnotes

Display footnote syntax:

This is a footnote marker: \[^1\]
Not a definition.

## Escaping Separators

Show separator syntax:

These are not separators:
---
\---
\***
\___

## Practical Examples

### Documentation of Syntax

To create bold text, use \*\*text\*\*.
To create italic text, use //text//.

### Code Tutorials

The function \`main()\` is the entry point.
Use \`\`\` for code blocks.

### Keyboard Shortcuts

Press \`Ctrl\` + \`C\` to copy.
Press \`Cmd\` + \`V\` to paste.

### File Paths

Windows: \`C:\\Users\\Name\\Documents\`
Note the double backslashes.

### Regular Expressions

Pattern: \`\\d{3}-\\d{2}-\\d{4}\`
Matches: 123-45-6789

### Markdown Examples

To write a link in Markdown: \[text\]\(url\)
To write an image: \!\[alt\]\(url\)

### Technical Documentation

Escape special characters in JSON:
\{ \\"key\\": \\"value\\" \}

### Code Comments

// This is not a Zolt comment
# Nor is this
%% Neither is this %%

## Complete Text Examples

### Syntax Guide

Welcome to the Zolt syntax guide!

\# Headers
Use \# for h1, \#\# for h2

\*Bold\* and //italic//
Use \*\* for bold, // for italic

\[Links\]\(urls)
Create links with \[text\]\(url\)

### Tutorial

Step 1: Create a file
Use \`\`\`filename.md\`\`\` or \`\`\`filename.zlt\`\`\`

Step 2: Write content
You can use \# headings, \- lists, and \> quotes

Step 3: Add styling
Use \{attr\} for attributes and \|\|text\|\|\{attr\} for inline styling

### Code Display

The backslash character: \\
The asterisk: \*
The underscore: \_
The bracket: \[
The brace: \{
The pipe: \|

## Complex Scenarios

### Mathematical Notation

In regex, use \\. for literal dot
In strings, use \\" for literal quote
In paths, use \\\\ for literal backslash

### Email Addresses

Contact: user\\@example.com
The \\ prevents auto-linking

### URLs as Text

Visit https:\\\\www.example.com
Or mailto:info\\@example.com

### Emoji and Special Characters

Copyright: \\u00A9 or \\©
Trademark: \\u2122 or \\™
Degree: \\u00B0 or \\°

### HTML Tags Display

The tag is \\<div class=\\"container\\">\\</div\\>
Not actual HTML

## Template Literals

JavaScript strings: \`\${variable}\`
Not Zolt variables

## Double Backslash

To display a literal backslash: \\\\
In Windows paths: C:\\\\Users\\\\Name

## Escape Sequences Reference

| Sequence | Result |
|----------|--------|
| \\ | Backslash |
| \[ | Literal [ |
| \] | Literal ] |
| \{ | Literal { |
| \} | Literal } |
| \| | Literal \| |
| \| \| | Literal \| \| |
| \* | Literal * |
| \# | Literal # |
| \- | Literal - |
| \. | Literal . |
| \! | Literal ! |
| \` | Literal ` |

## Real-World Examples

### Configuration File

# Database Settings
host: localhost
port: 5432
# Use \\ for escaped backslashes in paths

### Regular Expression Pattern

Pattern: \^\\d\{3\}-\\d\{2\}-\\d\{4\}\$
Matches: 123-45-6789

### JSON String

\{ \\"name\\": \\"John\\", \\"age\\": 30 \}

### Command Line Options

Usage: program \[options\] \[file\]

Options:
  \\-h, \\-\\-help     Show help
  \\-v, \\-\\-version  Show version

### File Extensions

Supported: \.md, \.zlt, \.txt
Not: \.exe, \.sh

## Common Pitfalls

### Don't Escape Normal Letters

This is \\a bad example (backslash before 'a' does nothing)
Use \\a only for special characters

### Don't Over-Escape

This is fine: [link](url)
No need to escape: \[link\]\(url\)

### Escape in Code Blocks

In regular text: \[not a link\]
In code blocks: [link](url) - no escaping needed

### Email Addresses

user@example.com - Will auto-link
user\@example.com - Will not auto-link

## Best Practices

1. Only escape when necessary
2. Escape special characters in documentation
3. Use code blocks for syntax examples
4. Test your escaped content
5. Remember: \\ escapes itself, use \\\\

